Author: Dav1d#7994
Content: why does javascript have `null` and `undefined`? they both seem to mean the same thing, `there's nothing here` and they are both falsey, as they should be. But it means, for example if I want to check if something exists but it could be `{}`, `[]`, `0` or some other falsey thing i have to check `if(thing !== undefined && thing !== null)`

Author: Erede#4825
Content: @Dav1d Actually due to a bug that was intentionally not fixed, null is equal to undefined if you use `==`

Author: Erede#4825
Content: But generally I think null and undefined have different meaning. Undefined tells you that this variable was never defined or does not exist in memory while null tells you that yes, it was defined but it is empty.

Certificates, if you can present one per year or so, might also indicate you are trying to stay up to date.

Author: Myke#3826
Content:
There are many collective names for ducks.  If the group of ducks is in the water they are called a raft. A group of ducklings is called a brood. A pair of ducks is called a brace. Here are some other terms from the British Bird Lovers organization:

Ducks (diving) - a dopping of ducks

ducks (flying) - a plump of ducks

ducks (on water) - a paddling of ducks

ducks - a badling of ducks

ducks - a flush of ducks

ducks - a raft of ducks

ducks - a sord of ducks

ducks - a team of ducks

ducks - a twack of ducks

Author: chuinzer#6740
Content:
import csv
import numpy as np
from sklearn.svm import SVR
import matplotlib.pylot as plt

dates = []
prices = []

def get_data(filename):
    with open(filename,'r') as csvfile:
        csvFileReader = csv.reader(csvfile)
        next(csvFileReader)
        for row in csvFileReader:
            dates.append(int(row[0].split('-')[0]))
            prices.append(float(row[1]))
    return

def predict_prices(dates,prices,x):
    dates = np.reshape(dates,(len(dates),1))

    svr_lin = SVR(kernel='linear',C=1e3)
    svr_poly = SVR(kernel='poly',C=1e3,degree = 2)
    svr_rbf = SVR(kernel='rbf',C=1e3,gamma=0.1)
    svr_lin.fit(dates,prices)
    svr_poly.fit(dates,prices)
    svr_rbf.fit(dates,prices)

    plt.scatter(dates,prices,color='black',label='Data')
    plt.plot(dates, svr_rbf.predict(dates),color='red',label='RBF model')
    plt.plot(dates, svr_lin.predict(dates),color='green',label='Linear model')
    plt.plot(dates, svr_poly.predict(dates),color='blue',label='Polynomial model')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Price')
    plt.title('Stock Predict')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    return svr_rbf.predict(x)[0],svr_lin.predict(x)[0],svr_poly.predict(x)[0]

get_data('aapl.csv')

predicted_price = predict_price(dates,prices,29)

print(predicted_price)

Author: Denial#5955
Content: Hello gamers, I'm new to CS50 too. I've been programming for a couple years now and have made some games before, as that has been my most convenient way of applying algorithms to my code (Such as breadth first search or depth first search), I saw a lot of people were talking about making games and asking others to join them

Author: Denial#5955
Content: If you want to colab with making a game (specially a 3d game) try unity. You can upload your progress to each other real-time, thus you can focus on different parts of the game and complete things much faster

Author: Denial#5955
Content: But I seriously suggest trying to make some games on your own first, specially on more difficult platforms, for example try to make a simple game using javafx (with java of course), if you try making a game this way you'll have a much clearer understanding of how children work, what transforms are, collisions, all that stuff. Don't try to go into 3d development if you haven't done anything 2d, or do, it's up to you haha.

Author: ToddTheSquid#2166
Content:
So I recently watched a video about a computer science paradox. Figured the people here could answer a question I had about it maybe?

Basically take a theoretical program that analyzes the code of any other program and decides whether that code will stop at some point, or loop infinitely. It outputs a yes if it stops or a no if it loops (called HALTS). Take another program that, if it gets a "yes" as input, it loops infinitely, and if it gets a "no", it stops (called OPPOSITE). Then combine those into a single program and feed its code into itself. The paradox says it can't be done because if it stops, it'd loop, but if it loops, it'd stop, and thus the initial program can't exist.

But here's my thoughts on it:

 I genuinely don't see the paradox here. I don't see why saying "HALTS(OPPOSITE,OPPOSITE)" won't work means that "HALTS" can't exist. Wouldn't that just mean that it would need more information, a larger input, of say "HALTS(OPPOSITE,OPPOSITE,OPPOSITE,OPPOSITE,...,I)" to theoretical infinity since the result of "OPPOSITE" is dependant on the input? Or even just stopping at an arbitrary point and adding the input? It's not that the program doesn't work, it's that you've fed it an incomplete input. That's user error, no fault of the program.

Basically, you can't determine the result of a program without first knowing its input. That's all this "paradox" says to me. Doesn't seem like a paradox at all to me, just faulty logic on the part of whoever thought it up (IIRC it was Turing who thought it up)

Author: ToddTheSquid#2166
Content: My question here is, am I right in the conclusion that the "paradox" is the result of user error and not a fault of the program itself?
